## Learning Mode (ALWAYS FOLLOW)

After every code change, explain to the user:

### 🔍 Why this file was changed
Explain the original problem and how this file is involved — not just "I changed X".

### ⚙️ How the logic works
Trace the data flow: where data comes from → what transforms it → where it goes.

### 🐛 Root cause (for bugs)
Identify the real root cause, not just the symptom.
- NOT "TypeError" → YES "API called before auth token was ready"
- NOT "undefined" → YES "async race condition in useEffect"

### ✨ Better ways to write this
If a better pattern exists, show it with reasoning:
- custom hook vs inline logic
- Zod schema vs manual validation
- separating concerns

### ⚠️ Edge cases not yet handled
List what could go wrong that the current code doesn't handle:
- network timeout
- null / empty values
- concurrent requests
- user navigating away mid-request

---

## Standard Workflow (ALWAYS FOLLOW THIS ORDER)

> **Read first → Think first → Change one part at a time → Always verify**
> Never skip steps, even for small tasks.

### Step 1 — Read the project
- Read this instruction file fully
- Read all files related to the task
- Understand imports/exports and dependencies

### Step 2 — Explain the structure
- Summarize what the code-to-be-changed currently does
- List all affected files
- Identify dependencies that could be impacted

### Step 3 — Plan before changing
- Write an ordered plan of what will change
- Explain any trade-offs and recommend the best option
- Wait for user approval if high-risk or large scope

### Step 4 — Change one part at a time
- Edit one file / one function at a time
- Explain each change as you make it
- Don't touch unrelated files

### Step 5 — Run build/lint
```bash
cd smart-charge-glow
bun lint      # must pass
bun build     # must succeed
```
- If lint errors → fix before commit
- If build fails → explain root cause to user

### Step 6 — Summarize the diff
Provide a table like:

| File | What changed | Why |
|------|-------------|-----|
| `src/xxx.ts` | Added error handling | Prevent crash on API timeout |

Then answer all 5 Learning Mode questions.

### Step 7 — Prepare commit message
Use Conventional Commits format:

```
<type>(<scope>): <short description>

<explain what & why — Thai or English>
```

Types: `feat`, `fix`, `refactor`, `chore`, `docs`, `style`, `test`

Example:
```
fix(tuya): handle API timeout gracefully

Added try/catch around fetchDeviceStatus to prevent crash
when Tuya API does not respond within 5 seconds.
Shows error toast instead of crashing the UI.
```
